				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\alpha }_{Kn}=\sqrt{\frac{{M}_{j}}{{M}_{i}}}$$\end{document}

Poiseuille flow occurs when the driving force for the diffusion is the pressure gradient between the feed and the permeate side. It usually happens with pore sizes of around 200 nm to 3,000 nm or when the membrane pore sizes are much greater than λ (r/λ > 3). It is also known as convective diffusion, which operates opposite to Knudsen diffusion. In contrast to Knudsen diffusion, this mechanism depicts gas diffusions through the molecular collisions instead of collisions with the pore walls. In Poiseuille flow, all the component molecules pass through the pores by an average drift velocity, independent of the shape, mass, and size of the molecules [74]. The molar flux is represented in Eq. 7, illustrating the Poiseuille flow mechanism [76, 82].7GP=r2(p1-p2)16L2μRT\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
